>Dedicated set times for writing

Anonymous Sat 04 Dec 2021 06:34:58 No.43694557 Report
Quoted By:
>>43692179
>I've seen it pay off in Call of the Waifur and no other story
… are you only browsing stories with the /adhg/ tag? You're leaving out Smiling's worldbuilding – which is extensive enough that it warrants its own docs – and Mousguy's BHA docs. Some authors can't focus on that aspect of their writing within the scopes of their stories (or are unable to exposit that information to the extent nor as quickly as they'd like), so they set that aside to let their plots run their course. I agree with the sentiment that fantasy and sci-fi settings benefit from solid in-story worldbuilding, but it's tricky to carry out in the scale of a short story, or plot-focused chapters. Other stories hint at larger-scale worldbuilding behind the scenes, like Where Kitsune Wait, while others throw it in your face, like MM. Acid Rain may not have the most depth, but I liked the sense of action and touch of suspense to it.

That said, I haven't seen many de jure write fags counsel new writers to focus on worldbuilding for some time now... I've been a cautious proponent of depthy worldbuilding myself, but a story's focus should be on its plot and characters. To their credit, most writers here don't try to expand their SOL urban romances into anything more than is necessary for plot progression and character development, which is as it should be.
